attributes.background:
Many people seeking asylum in the UK are mothers* fleeing war, persecution, rape and other torture; 

o To protect themselves and their children, mothers are often forced to leave their children behind – travelling together may put everyone at risk and usually they don’t know where they are going or how they will survive; 

o Mothers may lose contact with children back home or hear of them unprotected and suffering, and can do little to prevent it; 

o It can take many years for an asylum claim to be settled; but the pain of separation and of trying to be a carer long distance is invisible and unrecognised. 

o When mothers win the right to stay they are not automatically granted the right of family reunion. 

o If children turn 18 while their mother’s application is being considered they lose the right to join their mother.

See demands above.

Contact: Mothers’ Campaign of the All African Women’s Group, 020 7482 2496, aawg02@gmail.com

*We are a mothers’ campaign, so we speak particularly of mothers, the primary carers in every society, but we know that the problems and heartbreak we describe is often the same for fathers, grandparents and other carers.
